article.description: The Crimson Tide lost Sunday for the second time this season to No. 21 Arkansas, 68-57.
article.headline: Arkansas beats 'Bama for second time this season
article.linkText: Crimson Tide's bad luck continues against Arkansas
article.story:
FAYETTEVILLE, Ark. (AP) -- Alabama head basketball coach Rick
Moody isn't having good luck this season.

	   "What kind of luck is it that the last game of your season is
against Arkansas, at Arkansas, when they're 6-7 (in conference
play), on Senior Day, when they've got to win,'' Moody said. "And
then ... the SEC Tournament is in Arkansas and I get to ... play
them again.''

	   Moody's Crimson Tide lost Sunday for the second time this season
to Arkansas, 68-57, but he'll get a third shot as the two
teams meet Thursday in the Southeastern Conference Tournament in
North Little Rock.

	   Shameka Christon scored 25 points for the Lady Razorbacks (20-9,
7-7), who captured a much-needed win and the seventh seed, and the
Crimson Tide (13-14, 3-11) was named the 10th seed.

	   Arkansas (No. 19 ESPN/USA Today, No. 21 AP) and Alabama will meet at 2:30 p.m. in the first round
of the tournament.

	   On Sunday, the two teams duked it out on the court, trading
baskets and the lead until Arkansas hit a 13-6 run with four
minutes to play.

	   "It was typical Alabama-Arkansas,'' Moody said. "The last
several games we have played Arkansas have been outstanding games,
and I thought today's game was one of those.''

	   What hurt Alabama was fouls, as Arkansas was 23-of-26 at the
free-throw line, while Alabama had only four shots from the line,
three of which were completed, Moody said. Arkansas had 13 fouls,
while Alabama had 22.

	   "It's going to be very, very difficult to overcome those
numbers,'' Moody said. "As aggressive as they (Arkansas' defense)
are, that's what's ironic about shooting four free-throws, but
that's the breaks of the game.''

	   Beth Vice scored 18 points for the Crimson Tide (13-14, 3-11).
Natasha Gamble added 14, Monique Bivins had 12 and Jamilah Johns
had 11.

	   Alabama led 11-5 early, but the Lady Razorbacks tied the score
at 17 with nine minutes remaining until halftime.

	   "We tried to not talk about the pressure of this game, and we
really didn't, but it sure seemed like we opened up the game just
playing with the intensity that our lives depended on it because we
were missing easy shots,'' Arkansas head coach Gary Blair said.

	   The teams battled for the lead for the remainder of the period.
Kristin Moore hit two free throws to put Arkansas up 27-25 at
halftime.

	   Johns tipped in a basket to tie the game again in the opening
seconds of the second half, and Bivins' layup gave the Crimson Tide
a 29-27 lead.

	   Lakishia Harper tied the game at 31 with a short jumper. Then
Vice hit a 3-pointer from the left wing for a 34-33 lead.

	   Christon hit back-to-back 3s to put the Lady Razorbacks up by
three, but the lead was short-lived as Bivins hit her own 3 to tie
the game again at 43.

	   Shanna Harmon hit a 3 from the top of the arc, followed by two
free throws to give the Lady Razorbacks a 51-45 lead, but Vice was
left open for two 3s, bringing the Crimson Tide within two.

	   Arkansas went on a 13-6 run with less than four minutes left to
play, and Cherry finished with four free throws seal it for
Arkansas.

	   "It was one of those games that we were never in control of
it,'' Blair said. "They were not in control of it. It was sort of
an ugly game to watch. But at the same time, both teams were laying
it out on the line.''
